### NTS Pool Experiment
David provided an update on the experimental Network Time Security (NTS) pool:
* An experimental pool is currently running at `sectime.org` utilizing the specification defined in `draft-ietf-ntp-nts-keyexchange-pool`.
* The draft has been updated to include early allocations and a new session flow section to provide additional context.
* There are currently about 20 active servers in the pool, and the team is seeking more users to test against it.

### NTS Pools using DNS SRV Records
A presenter introduced a secondary experimental pool project running at `srv.sectime.org`, referencing the presentation [NTS Server Pools using DNS SRV records](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-ntp-nts-server-pools-using-dns-srv-records-00).
* **Architecture**: The standard `pool.ntp.org` model relies on DNS A/AAAA records, which is insecure for NTS because it would require sharing a TLS certificate among all pool servers. Instead, this experiment utilizes DNS SRV records, enabling each server to maintain its own certificate.
* **Security Properties**: The architecture requires that clients can cryptographically verify pool membership via DNSSEC. However, DNSSEC does not protect against replay attacks. While keeping TTLs and signing durations low or increasing the response size can mitigate this, these compromises reduce DNS caching benefits and increase server load.
* **Challenges**: 
  * Unlike the pool design in `draft-ietf-ntp-nts-keyexchange-pool`, SRV records lack a graceful fallback for clients that are not pool-aware.
  * Client implementation complexity increases significantly due to the requirement to perform DNSSEC verification. Local stub and recursive resolvers frequently do not support DNSSEC validation, strip DNSSEC records, or contain validation bugs. 
  * Manual root key rollouts remain a hurdle for non-updatable clients.
* **Path Forward**: The experiment will continue running for at least a year to gather empirical performance and caching data.

### NTS for PTP
The Chairperson provided a status update on `draft-ietf-ntp-nts-for-ptp`:
* Active development on this draft has slowed within the IETF because the core security work is currently occurring within the IEEE 1588 committee. Once that work achieves consensus, the draft will be updated to align with it.

### Hackathon Report
David presented the results of the IETF 126 Hackathon, referencing the [Hackathon](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-ntp-hackathon-00) slides:
* **NTS Pool (`draft-ietf-ntp-nts-keyexchange-pool`)**: Participants fixed IPv4 handling bugs in the experimental pool, assisted new servers in joining, and successfully demonstrated the pool during the Hack Demo Happy Hour.
* **NTPv5 (`draft-ietf-ntp-ntpv5`)**: Sarah developed an interoperability test harness. Testing revealed interoperability bugs between Chrony and `ntp-rs`, specifically regarding version negotiation during the upgrade process. Sarah noted that when a client initiates a connection with NTPv4 and signals NTPv5 support, some servers fail to acknowledge the upgrade, causing the session to remain NTPv4. 
* **Roughtime**: Testing was extended to cover both UDP and TCP. However, TCP is not yet widely supported. Sarah pointed out that many implementations are using incompatible, outdated versions of the Roughtime specification. Sarah suggested waiting for RFC publication (which will trigger a version bump) to simplify client control and fallback testing.

### IEEE 1588 Update
The Chairperson presented the [IEEE 1588 Update](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-ntp-ieee-1588-update-00):
* The IEEE 1588 committee has several active projects, including a roll-up revision, asymmetry calibration, and Client-Server PTP (CSPTP).
* **PTP Security**: The security subcommittee is focusing on addressing PTP vulnerabilities, adding NTS as a key management mechanism, and defining security datasets. The Chairperson anticipates having these updates finalized within the next 6 to 10 months. Martin and Reiner are expected to update `draft-ietf-ntp-nts-for-ptp` by fall to reflect this progress.
* **CSPTP**: For security purposes, CSPTP behaves similarly to NTP. David has submitted an initial proposal to use NTS for CSPTP, building on proof-of-concept work completed at a previous IETF hackathon.

### ITU Study Group 17 Liaison
The Chairperson reported that the working group received a liaison request from ITU Study Group 17 concerning the upcoming 2036-2038 time rollovers. The documents have been posted to the NTP mailing list for review.

